```
import java.util.*;

public class ShortestPath {
    public static String shortestPath(String[] graph) {
        int n = Integer.parseInt(graph[0]);
        Map<String, List<String>> adjList = new HashMap<>();
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            adjList.put(graph[i], new ArrayList<>());
        }
        for (int i = n + 1; i < graph.length; i++) {
            String[] nodes = graph[i].split("-");
            adjList.get(nodes[0]).add(nodes[1]);
            adjList.get(nodes[1]).add(nodes[0]);
        }
        String start = graph[1];
        String end = graph[n];
        Set<String> visited = new HashSet<>();
        Map<String, String> prev = new HashMap<>();
        Queue<String> queue = new ArrayDeque<>();
        queue.offer(start);
        visited.add(start);
        while (!queue.isEmpty()) {
            String node = queue.poll();
            for (String neighbor : adjList.get(node)) {
                if (!visited.contains(neighbor)) {
                    visited.add(neighbor);
                    prev.put(neighbor, node);
                    queue.offer(neighbor);
                }
            }
            if (node.equals(end)) {
                List<String> path = new ArrayList<>();
                while (node != null) {
                    path.add(node);
                    node = prev.get(node);
                }
                Collections.reverse(path);
                return String.join("-", path);
            }
        }
        return "-1";
    }
}
```

First, we create an adjacency list from the input, which maps each node to its neighbors. We also keep track of the start and end nodes, and initialize a set of visited nodes, a map of previous nodes, and a queue of nodes to visit. We begin by adding the start node to the queue, marking it as visited, and repeatedly processing the next node in the queue, adding its unvisited neighbors to the queue and marking them as visited. If we ever encounter the end node while processing a neighbor, we have found the shortest path from the start to the end, which we can reconstruct by following the previous node pointers back from the end to the start.

The time complexity of this solution is O(n + e), where n is the number of nodes and e is the number of edges in the graph. The space complexity is also O(n + e), since we need to store the adjacency list, visited set, previous node map, and queue.

