Here is the completed code for the myIntegral function, which calculates the area under a curve using three different methods (Left Riemann, Right Riemann, and Trapezoidal) and compares them to the true benchmark value calculated by MATLAB's "integral" function:

```MATLAB
function [intg, best] = myIntegral(range, N, f)

  % Calculate the true integral using MATLAB's "integral" function
  Itrue = integral(f, range(1), range(2));

  % Calculate the step size
  delta_x = (range(2) - range(1)) / N;

  % Left Riemann
  Ileft = sum(arrayfun(f, [range(1):delta_x:range(2)-delta_x])) * delta_x;

  % Right Riemann
  Iright = sum(arrayfun(f, [range(1)+delta_x:delta_x:range(2)])) * delta_x;

  % Trapezoidal
  Itrap = sum(arrayfun(f, [range(1):delta_x:range(2)])) * delta_x - 0.5 * (f(range(1)) + f(range(2))) * delta_x;

  % Save the results in the "intg" cell array
  intg = [{'Left Riemann'}, {'Right Riemann'}, {'Trapezoidal'}; {Ileft}, {Iright}, {Itrap}];

  % Calculate the differences with the true integral value
  diff_intg = abs([Ileft, Iright, Itrap] - Itrue);

  % Determine which method had the smallest difference
  [~, best_idx] = min(diff_intg);

  % Set the output variable "best" to the best method's name
  best = intg{1, best_idx};

end
```

