The transformation matrix B(q) that maps body-fixed angular velocities to Euler angle rates is called the body-to-Euler rate matrix or the Jacobian matrix.

Here are the 12 sequences of rotation along with their corresponding body-to-Euler rate matrices:

1. Z-X'-Z": B(q) = [cos(θ), 0, -cos(φ)*sin(θ); 
                    0, 1, sin(φ); 
                    sin(θ), 0, cos(φ)*cos(θ)]

2. Z-Y'-Z": B(q) = [cos(θ), -sin(φ)*sin(θ), 0; 
                    sin(φ), cos(φ)*cos(θ), 0; 
                    0, sin(θ), cos(φ)*cos(θ)]

3. X-Y-X": B(q) = [1, sin(φ)*tan(θ), cos(φ)*tan(θ); 
                   0, cos(φ), -sin(φ); 
                   0, sin(φ)/cos(θ), cos(φ)/cos(θ)]

4. X-Z-X": B(q) = [cos(θ), 0, -sin(θ); 
                   0, 1, 0; 
                   sin(θ), 0, cos(θ)*cos(φ)/cos(θ)]

5. Y-Z-Y": B(q) = [cos(φ)*cos(θ)/cos(θ), -sin(φ), 0; 
                   sin(φ)/cos(θ), cos(φ), 0; 
                   0, 0, 1]

6. Y-X-Y": B(q) = [cos(φ)*cos(θ), -sin(φ), 0; 
                   sin(φ)*cos(θ), cos(φ)*cos(θ), 0; 
                   0, sin(θ), 1]

7. Z'-Y''-Z''': B(q) = [cos(θ), sin(φ)*sin(θ), 0; 
                        -sin(φ)*sin(θ), cos(θ), 0; 
                        0, 0, 1]

8. X'-Y''-X''': B(q) = [cos(φ)*cos(θ), -sin(φ), 0; 
                        sin(φ)*cos(θ), cos(φ)*cos(θ), 0; 
                        sin(θ), -sin(φ)*cos(θ), 1]

9. Y'-X''-Y''': B(q) = [cos(θ), 0, -sin(θ); 
                        0, 1, 0; 
                        sin(θ), 0, cos(θ)]

10. Y'-Z''-Y''': B(q) = [cos(φ)*cos(θ)/cos(θ), 0, -sin(φ)/cos(θ); 
                        0, 1, 0; 
                        sin(φ)/cos(θ), 0, cos(φ)*cos(θ)/cos(θ)]

11. Z'-X''-Z''': B(q) = [cos(θ)*cos(φ), sin(θ)*cos(φ), -sin(φ); 
                        -cos(θ)*sin(φ), -sin(θ)*sin(φ), -cos(φ); 
                        sin(θ), -cos(θ), 0]

12. X'-Z''-X''': B(q) = [1, 0, -sin(θ); 
                        0, cos(φ), sin(φ)*cos(θ); 
                        0, -sin(φ), cos(φ)*cos(θ)]

To transform from Euler angle rates to angular velocities, we can use the following formula:

[ω_x, ω_y, ω_z]^T = B(q)^-1 * [φ_dot, θ_dot, ψ_dot]^T

where B(q)^-1 is the inverse of the body-to-Euler rate matrix, and [φ_dot, θ_dot, ψ_dot]^T represents the time derivatives of Euler angles. The resulting vector [ω_x, ω_y, ω_z]^T represents the angular velocities along the X, Y, and Z axes, respectively, with respect to the body-fixed coordinate system.

There are actually 24 Euler rotation sequences, as each of the 12 can be done with either intrinsic or extrinsic rotations. We will list the 12 intrinsic rotation sequences first, followed by the 12 extrinsic rotation sequences.

1. XYZ (Roll-Pitch-Yaw) Sequence:
B(q) = [ 1  sin(phi)*tan(theta)  cos(phi)*tan(theta);
            0         cos(phi)                -sin(phi);
            0  sin(phi)/cos(theta)  cos(phi)/cos(theta) ]
where q = [phi, theta, psi] and the sequence of rotations is roll about x, pitch about y, and then yaw about z.

2. XZY Sequence:
B(q) = [ 1  sin(theta)*tan(phi)  cos(theta)*tan(phi);
            0         cos(theta)                -sin(theta);
            0  sin(theta)/cos(phi)  cos(theta)/cos(phi) ]
where q = [phi, theta, psi] and the sequence of rotations is roll about x, pitch about z, and then yaw about y.

3. YZX Sequence:
B(q) = [ cos(theta)*cos(psi)                                        -cos(theta)*sin(psi)                                          sin(theta);
            cos(phi)*sin(psi)+sin(phi)*sin(theta)*cos(psi)  cos(phi)*cos(psi)-sin(phi)*sin(theta)*sin(psi) -sin(phi)*cos(theta);
            sin(phi)*sin(psi)-cos(phi)*sin(theta)*cos(psi)  sin(phi)*cos(psi)+cos(phi)*sin(theta)*sin(psi)  cos(phi)*cos(theta) ]
where q = [phi, theta, psi] and the sequence of rotations is roll about y, pitch about z, and then yaw about x.

4. YXZ Sequence:
B(q) = [ cos(theta)*cos(psi)  -sin(psi)  cos(psi)*sin(theta);
            cos(phi)*sin(psi)*sin(theta)+sin(phi)*cos(psi)  cos(phi)*cos(psi)-sin(phi)*sin(psi)*sin(theta)  -cos(theta)*sin(phi);
            sin(phi)*sin(psi)-cos(phi)*cos(psi)*sin(theta)  sin(phi)*cos(psi)*sin(theta)+cos(phi)*sin(psi)  cos(phi)*cos(theta) ]
where q = [phi, theta, psi] and the sequence of rotations is roll about y, pitch about x, and then yaw about z.

5. ZYX Sequence:
B(q) = [ cos(theta)*cos(psi)  cos(theta)*sin(psi)  -sin(theta);
            -cos(phi)*sin(psi)+sin(phi)*sin(theta)*cos(psi)  cos(phi)*cos(psi)+sin(phi)*sin(theta)*sin(psi)  sin(phi)*cos(theta);
            sin(phi)*sin(psi)+cos(phi)*sin(theta)*cos(psi)  -sin(phi)*cos(psi)+cos(phi)*sin(theta)*sin(psi)  cos(phi)*cos(theta) ]
where q = [phi, theta, psi] and the sequence of rotations is roll about z, pitch about y, and then yaw about x.

6. ZXY Sequence:
B(q) = [ cos(theta)*cos(psi)-sin(phi)*sin(theta)*sin(psi)  -cos(psi)*sin(phi)*sin(theta)-cos(theta)*sin(psi)  cos(phi)*sin(theta);
            cos(phi)*cos(psi)                                        -sin(phi)*cos(psi)                                        -sin(phi);
            cos(phi)*sin(theta)*sin(psi)+cos(theta)*cos(psi)  cos(phi)*cos(theta)*sin(psi)-sin(phi)*cos(psi)  cos(phi)*cos(theta) ]
where q = [phi, theta, psi] and the sequence of rotations is roll about z, pitch about x, and then yaw about y.

7. XYX Sequence:
B(q) = [ 1  0        0;
            0  cos(phi) -sin(phi);
            0  sin(phi)  cos(phi) ]
where q = [phi, theta, psi] and the sequence of rotations is roll about x, pitch about y, and then roll again about x.

8. XZX Sequence:
B(q) = [ 1  0         0;
            0  cos(phi) sin(phi);
            0 -sin(phi) cos(phi) ]
where q = [phi, theta, psi] and the sequence of rotations is roll about x, pitch about z, and then roll again about x.

9. YXY Sequence:
B(q) = [ cos(phi) 0 sin(phi);
            0        1 0;
            -sin(phi) 0 cos(phi) ]
where q = [phi, theta, psi] and the sequence of rotations is roll about y, pitch about x, and then roll again about y.

10. YZY Sequence:
B(q) = [ cos(phi) -sin(phi) 0;
            sin(phi)  cos(phi)  0;
            0           0              1 ]
where q = [phi, theta, psi] and the sequence of rotations is roll about y, pitch about z, and then roll again about y.

11. ZXZ Sequence:
B(q) = [ cos(phi)  sin(phi)  0;
            -sin(phi) cos(phi)  0;
            0             0               1 ]
where q = [phi, theta, psi] and the sequence of rotations is roll about z, pitch about x, and then roll again about z.

12. ZYZ Sequence:
B(q) = [ cos(phi) -sin(phi) 0;
            sin(phi)  cos(phi)  0;
            0           0              1 ]
where q = [phi, theta, psi] and the sequence of rotations is roll about z, pitch about y, and then roll again about z.

Now the 12 extrinsic rotation sequences:

13. XYZ Sequence:
B(q) = [ cos(theta)*cos(psi)                                        -cos(theta)*sin(psi)                                          sin(theta);
            cos(phi)*sin(psi)+sin(phi)*sin(theta)*cos(psi)  cos(phi)*cos(psi)-sin(phi)*sin(psi)*sin(theta)  -sin(phi)*cos(theta);
            sin(phi)*sin(psi)-cos(phi)*sin(theta)*cos(psi)  sin(phi)*cos(psi)+cos(phi)*sin(psi)*sin(theta)  cos(phi)*cos(theta) ]
where q = [phi, theta, psi] and the sequence of rotations is yaw about z, pitch about y, and then roll about x.

